-- Crude Options Volatility Rises as Futures Slide on Fed Taper
-- B y   E l i o t   C a r o o m
-- 2013-08-21T20:51:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-21/crude-options-volatility-rises-as-futures-slide-on-fed-taper.html
Crude oil options volatility rose as
futures dropped on Federal Reserve minutes that signaled a
likely reduction this year in economic stimulus.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October was 22.69 percent on the  New York  Mercantile Exchange at
4:25 p.m., up from 22.21 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for October delivery fell
$1.26 to settle at $103.85 a barrel on the Nymex, the lowest
level in almost two weeks.  The most active options in electronic trading today were
October $117 calls, which fell 5 cents to 7 cents a barrel on
volume of 3,228 lots as of 4:30 p.m. October $116 calls were
second-most active, dropping 8 cents to 8 cents a barrel on
3,175 contracts.  Calls made up 62 percent of electronic trading volume. In
the prior session, bearish bets represented 59 percent of the
139,033 contracts exchanged.  October $97.50 puts were the most-active options yesterday
with 13,731 lots exchanging hands as they rose 23 cents to 54
cents a barrel. October $100 puts gained 36 cents to 92 cents on
volume of 5,223 contracts.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
39,889 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 35,727 lots
and December $105 calls with 35,712.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eliot Caroom in New York at 
 ecaroom@bloomberg.net  